stylometry: Decision trees are unique to other decision theory methods because when you create a decision tree, you are able the sequentially see the tradeoffs between each decision. So instead of a payoff table which may be somewhat one-dimensional, you can see how one decision affects the decision following, and the decision after that, and so on and so forth. We use decision trees in managing when we need to decide new ways to utilize assets. So maybe we have a large amount of surplus money and we want to invest it to grow the money further. So then we may decide whether we want to invest in the stock market, put it in the bank and grow it by interest, or send it with Bob to the race track so he can bet it all. Each of these decision has a different probability of outcomes and also a different EMV (expected monetary value) at the end. So by making a decision tree, we can go through each possibility sequentially and determine the best possible outcome for investing the money (I wouldn't suggest sending it to the race track).
